    08/02/11 at 3:59 pm  </span>
  <span class="editcomment"> 
    </span>
  <p class="content"><p>@ajohnson1986</p>
<p>This wouldn’t be very useful for DoD purposes because of the short range.  I don’t know how far Wi-Fi signals penetrate the atmosphere, but the curvature of the earth will certainly be a problem.   If you tried to drop a LocataLite guided bomb in Iran for example, it would have to use Iran’s LocataLite network to guide the bomb.  If they don’t have a LocataLite network, or they decide to turn their network off, that would be a problem.  Not to mention warships at sea.</p>
<p>This is not really a replacement for GPS because it is not global.  But it would be very useful for civilian purposes in population centers.  </p>
<p>BTW, military GPS receivers are more accurate than the devices available to civilians.  I don’t know if  governments will like a hyper accurate positioning tech on the commercial market.</p>
</p>
